INTRODUCTION

The International Conference on the Computer Processing of Oriental
Languages (ICCPOL) series is a regular international conference =
supported by
the Chinese and Oriental Languages Society (COLCS), an international =
society
founded in 1975.=20

=20

Recent ICCPOLs have been held in Hong Kong (1997), Tokushima, Japan =
(1999),
Seoul, Korea (2001) and Shenyang, China (2003). The 2006 Conference will =
be
the 21st gathering.=20

=20

The conference serves as an international forum for linguists, computer
scientists, information engineers and system users with interests in the
computer processing and understanding of Oriental languages. Topics of
interest include, but are not limited to

=20

*	Cross- and multilingual information processing
*	Text input methods=20
*	Document analysis and character recognition=20
*	Natural language processing=20
*	Machine translation
*	Information retrieval and extraction
*	Question Answering
*	Text Summarization
*	Multilingual computing
*	Speech recognition and synthesis
*	Language resources and evaluation
*	Web-based applications
*	E-commerce, education and entertainment

=20

High quality papers presenting innovative ideas, design principles,
theoretical analysis, implementation techniques, programming concepts, =
and
experimental results are solicited.=20

=20

SUBMISSION GUIDELINES



The proceedings of the conference will be published as a volume in the
Springer LNCS/LNAI series.  All submissions must therefore be formatted =
in
accordance with the standard Springer style sheets ([LaTeX
<http://www.springeronline.com/sgw/cda/pageitems/document/cda_downloaddoc=
ume
nt/0,11996,0-0-45-72915-0,00.zip> ][Microsoft Word
<http://www.springeronline.com/sgw/cda/pageitems/document/cda_downloaddoc=
ume
nt/0,11996,0-0-45-72919-0,00.zip> ]) and should be no more than 8 pages =
in
length. Submissions should be in PDF format.

=20

Authors should specify a preference for ORAL or POSTER presentation.=20

=20

Submission details will be provided on the conference website.



For more information about paper submission, please contact Richard =
Sproat
(rws@uiuc.edu) or Yuji Matsumoto (matsu@is.nist.ac.jp).


